<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>A rare black leopard was caught on camera as it crossed the road while hunting deer at a national park. </p>

<p>Anurag Gawande was amazed to see the predator as it emerged from the bushes at Tadoba National Park, India.</p>

<p>The 24-year-old described the encounter as 'unique' and 'like finding a needle in haystack'.</p>

<p>The animal's dark coat is caused by melanism - when extra black pigment develops in the skin or hair because of a recessive genetic mutation. </p>

<p>There are only 2,000 black leopards in the wild with most found in Southeast Asia where tropical forests offer an abundance of shade.</p>

<p>It is thought that melanism provides additional camouflage in these habitats which gives the predators an advantage when it comes to hunting. </p>

